        }
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here are the results for the article by McGraw and Wong on the Common Language Effect Size Statistic:\n\n## McGraw, K. O., & Wong, S. P. (1992). \"A Common Language Effect Size Statistic.\" *Psychological Bulletin*, 111(2), 361–365.\n\n**Citation details:**\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Authors: Kenneth O. McGraw and S. P. Wong, published March 1992 in *Psychological Bulletin*, Volume 111, pages 361–365."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "DOI: 10.1037/0033-2909.111.2.361"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n**Key concept:**\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Some of the shortcomings in interpretability and generalizability of the effect size statistics currently available to researchers can be overcome by a statistic that expresses how often a score sampled from one distribution will be greater than a score sampled from another distribution."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The statistic, the common language effect size indicator, is easily calculated from sample means and variances (or from proportions in the case of nominal-level data)."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n**Illustrative example:**\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "The example they gave was based on data from the US National Center for Health Statistics, showing the mean height of men to be 69.7 inches (standard deviation 2.8 inches) and of women 64.3 inches (standard deviation 2.6 inches)."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": " "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "If both height distributions are assumed to be normal, then the probability that a randomly selected man will be taller than a randomly selected woman turns out to be .92 or 92 per cent."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n**Extensions in the paper:**\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "McGraw and Wong introduced this \"common language effect size statistic\" for normal distributions and then proposed an approximate estimation for any continuous distribution. In addition, they generalized CL to the n-group case, the correlated samples case, and the discrete values case."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n**Available at:**\n- APA PsycNet: https://psycnet.apa.org/record/1992-18415-001\n- Semantic Scholar: https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/816d070fe2f62eac3e0ae4e8bc08eaa3f16cb800\n- ResearchGate: https://www.researchgate.net/publication/232493691"
      }
    ],
